<HL>
   U.S. Contends Exports
   Of Mexican Cement
   Are Unfairly Priced
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2F
</SO>
<CO>
   C.CMX C.CMT
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BUILDING MATERIALS (BLD)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Commerce Department ruled that Mexican
companies are exporting hydraulic cement to the U.S. at
unfairly low prices.
   The preliminary anti-dumping decision will require
importers of Mexican cement and clinker, an intermediate
material, to post bonds or make cash payments to cover
penalty duties that may be assessed later.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The department's final ruling is due by June 19, after
which the U.S. International Trade Commission would decide
within 45 days whether the imports were injuring a domestic
industry. If both findings are affirmative, penalty duties
would be assessed.
   The department said the imports of cement and clinker
totaled about $111 million last year. The dumping margins,
and thus the potential duties, range as high as 56.68% for
cement produced by Cemex S.A.. The margin is 51.73% for
Apasco S.A. de C.V. and 51.16% for most other companies.
However, one Mexican producer, Cementos Hidalgo S.C.L.,
hasn't exported cement or clinker to the U.S. at unfairly low
prices, the agency said.
   Under the Anti-Dumping Act, the Commerce Department can
find a violation if imports are reaching the U.S. market at
prices below the producer's home-market price for the same
products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
