<HL>
   Business Brief -- Valmont Industries Inc.:
   Official Indicates Earnings
   For Quarter Held Steady
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7D
</SO>
<CO>
   VALM
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Analyst projections that Valmont Industries Inc. will
report per-share net income in the range of 33 cents to 36
cents for its first quarter, ended April 1, represent a "fair
estimate," William F. Welsh II, president and chief executive
officer, said.
   Those results would equal or fall slightly below the
Omaha, Neb., company's year-ago net of $4.2 million, or 36
cents a share, on revenue of $189.4 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Valmont makes irrigation systems, industrial products
including steel poles and tubing, and additionally holds an
82% stake in ValCom Inc., a reseller of personal computers.
   The company's irrigation business will have an "excellent
year" in 1990, but "not quite as strong" as it has been in
the past couple of years, when drought conditions spurred
sales in the Farm Belt, Mr. Welsh said in an interview. The
improved health of the general farm economy this year, he
said, will help offset the absence of a "drought situation."
Domestic demand remains "strong," he said, adding that the
company's export market -- which covers some 70 nations -- is
also "quite good."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900409-0139
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900409-0139.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Ratings
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   USW
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   U S WEST Inc. (Denver) -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it
lowered its senior debt ratings of three U S West units --
BetaWest Properties, U S West Capital Funding Inc. and U S
West Financial Services -- from A-plus to double-A-minus. S&amp;P
also downgraded the senior debt ratings of U S West
Communications Group to double-A-minus from double-A. S&amp;P
affirmed U S West Capital Funding's commercial paper at
A1-plus and U S West Communications Group's commercial paper
at A1-plus. S&amp;P said the change reflects 1989 consolidated
debt leverage of 51.8% of total capitalization, of which
about 53% consists of U S West Communications debt
obligations. Moreover, S&amp;P said U S West has been
diversifying into higher-risk ventures, such as financial
services and cellular telephone. S&amp;P also attributed the
downgrade to increasing business risk in the company's
telephone service areas, which the rating firm said hadn't
been offset by improved financial support for credit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
