   International:
   German Economic Growth
   Revised Sharply Upward
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRANKFURT, West Germany -- West Germany's five leading
research institutes revised their economic-growth forecasts
upward sharply for both this year and next, the newspaper
Welt am Sonntag reported.
   The research institutes are now projecting 1990 growth
could reach 4%, equal to last year's strong expansion and
above their earlier estimates of between 3% and 3.5%, the
newspaper said. They revised their growth forecast for 1991
to 3.5% from 2.5%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The institutes said the unification of the two Germanys
was giving the economy an extra push. Their spring report
won't be officially released until today.
</TEXT>
