<HL>
   Media:
   CBS Gets First TV Rights
   For MCA's 1989 Movies
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   MCA CBS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   For the first time in more than a decade, a television
network has won first-run TV rights from a major movie
studio, bypassing the usual sales to cable TV.
   Industry officials say an as-yet undisclosed pact signed
between CBS Inc. and MCA Inc.'s Universal Pictures unit will
provide the third-place network with all of Universal's
direct 1989 releases, including the box-office hits "Field of
Dreams" and "Born on the Fourth of July."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Details of the agreement weren't available. People in the
industry speculate that CBS will pay about $50 million for
rights to run the films during its 1990-1991 season. Network
officials couldn't be reached. A spokesman for Universal
declined to comment.
   Analysts said the pact is a striking departure from recent
industry patterns, in which rights to feature films (after
theater showings) are sold for video distribution, then cable
broadcast, and finally -- at a sharply reduced price -- to
the three major TV networks.
   "This is going back to the good old days," said Alan
Kassan, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton.
   Although Universal's contract with CBS appears a marriage
of convenience impelled by unusual circumstances on both
sides, the pact may foreshadow changes in relationships
between the major movie studios and cable TV services, some
analysts say. "I fully expect that the networks will be
bidding heavily with pay TV for movie rights in the next few
years," said Steven Rosenberg, head of his own consulting
firm, Rose Media Corp., in Pebble Beach, Calif. He says
networks are relying increasingly on major sporting events
and perhaps blockbuster movies to promote other parts of
their programming lineups.
   CBS's purchase of the film rights raises questions about
the strength of its programming lineup. "The network, with
its weak prime-time ratings, needs to look for a new
strategy, particularly for the sweeps," said Mr. Kassan. The
sweeps are the four-times-a-year rating periods that test the
relative popularity of television programming.
   For MCA and Universal, the agreement fulfills a
longstanding drive to circumvent Time Warner Inc.'s Home Box
Office and Viacom Inc.'s Showtime/The Movie Channel, whose
dominance of pay television gives the two cable empires
paramount positions in bidding for movie rights.
   That dominance not long ago led MCA's mercurial president,
Sidney J. Sheinberg, to threaten that the company not only
would try to sell movies directly to the major networks, but
might even seek informal networks of local stations to
exhibit Universal films.
   Antipathies between MCA and the cable barons apparently
remain high. MCA and Universal's talks with Home Box Office
to renew a recently expired five-year movie-rights pact were
particularly difficult, people in the industry say. Analysts
believe the pay-TV company paid far too much for rights in
the earlier pact for what proved a weak movie lineup and thus
was determined to keep the price down on any new arrangement.
Home Box Office officials couldn't be reached for comment.
   At the same time, the popularity of Universal's film
offerings improved markedly last year, convincing the studio
that it should be paid more for any new contract.
   The 10 1989 movies CBS will pick up first-run rights to
include producer-director Spike Lee's critical success "Do
the Right Thing;" "Sea of Love," with Al Pacino; "Uncle
Buck," starring John Candy; "K-9," starring Jim Belushi; as
well as "Field of Dreams" and "Born on the Fourth of July."
Also included in the package are less popular features:
"Fletch Lives," "Renegades," "Shocker," and "The Wizard," a
dud about a youthful video-game whiz.
   The agreement apparently excludes movies by Imagine Films
Entertainment Inc., which under a separate arrangement have
been sold to Showtime, with subsequent broadcasts arranged
with CBS. Imagine, a separate company, has close ties to
Universal in its feature film production and distribution.
Imagine's 1989 movies include "The Burbs," "The Dream Team,"
and "Parenthood," one of the year's better-grossing films.
   Also excluded are movies of Steven Spielberg's Amblin
Entertainment Co., including "Dad," "Back to the Future, Part
2" and "Always."
   It's not clear whether MCA will win or lose revenue in the
short term with its prospective end run around pay
television. Mr. Kassan estimated that the company took in
about $120 million in revenue last year from pay cable
licensing. Of that total, about $85 million came from Home
Box Office and the remainder from Showtime, he said.
   If industry speculation is correct that revenue from the
CBS pact will be around $50 million, then the television
broadcast rights may fall short of last year, although
revenue from Imagine Films and Amblin Entertainment may fill
in much of the gap.
   An equally important question remains for CBS: Will it get
an audience response that justifies its outlays -- whatever
they may be?
   Before home video rentals and pay TV entered the equation,
networks could count on big ratings for blockbuster movies.
But analysts question whether a prospective audience, gorged
on $2 home video rentals, will sit through a critically
esteemed movie interrupted by commercials. In some cases,
research suggests audiences accept only certain "franchise"
films, such as Sylvester Stallone's beefcake melodramas or
James Bond movies, with commercial breaks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900409-0048
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900409-0048.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   After Poindexter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   He is a victim of a concerted action by Congress, working
hand-in-glove with the independent counsel's office to try to
do something with this political battle.
   -- Richard Beckler, lawyer for John Poindexter, to the
jury.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   {Do not consider} who was right in political disputes
between Congress and the president, between Democrats and
Republicans or between liberals and conservatives.
   -- Judge Greene, instructing the jury.
                                                                                                       

   {There's no question that even being charitable to Admiral
Poindexter, he did it because he wanted to protect the
political viability of Ronald Reagan. And I consider that to
be a selfish motive.}
   -- Independent counsel prosecutor Dan Webb after the
verdict.
                                                                                                       

   What has been resolved by the Iran-Contra trials, what has
been established? Congress and the Democratic Party have
achieved a victory of sorts. A jury has declared that John
Poindexter violated congressional law by not being frank
enough in his dealings with Congress. Politics goes on,
though, and it's a little ironic how far away politics has
moved from the original substance of this dispute.
   For example, is the Poindexter verdict a repudiation of
President Reagan's Nicaragua policy? Judge Greene's directive
notwithstanding, that of course is a political question. On
the evidence, the policy is a success. Congressional policy
was to stop the Contras from pressuring the Soviet-supported
Sandinista government. Despite the five anti-Contra Boland
amendments, the White House did keep the Contras alive body
and soul, and they made Sandinista consolidation impossible.
When the Nicaraguans got to vote, they removed the
Sandinistas from power.
   On the legal side, if the Iran-Contra convictions are
upheld on appeal we will have some very curious precedents.
President Reagan was forced to testify, but Judge Greene
refused to subpoena 65 congressmen. Mr. Poindexter's lawyers
wanted to show that Members were not deceived because they
knew before Mr. Poindexter's testimony about aid to the
Contras and the missile shipment to Iran. In other words, we
may never know what congressmen knew and when they knew it.
Those who say the Poindexter case shows that the President
isn't above the law profess no concern that Congress is far
above the law.
   Treating criminal trials as an extension of partisan
politics leaves the President's political status vis a vis
Congress pretty much where it was. Congress will keep trying
to commandeer presidential power by any means so long as the
President fails to guard his office. One likely change is
that on advice of counsel, executive-branch officials will
almost certainly be less frank in their congressional
testimony, lest in difficult matters they become the target
of a congressman's demand for a special prosecutor.
   This congressional criminalizing of policy differences
with the executive branch will probably only end when the
Democrats think they have some prospect of regaining the
presidency. They now pay no price for substituting litigation
for politics. They are happy for judges and juries to become
a proxy for the electorate -- except that in the Ollie North
and Poindexter trials the juror-voters had to convince the
court that they knew nothing whatsoever about the political
life of the country. The judiciary might ask itself if it
really wants to play the top role in this brutal political
game.
   For the larger electorate, Iran-Contra will be remembered
for the televised hearings which gave ample opportunity for
the public to form its opinion of the matter. For President
Reagan and his treatment by history, Iran-Contra will likely
be a footnote against the fall of communism -- including in
Nicaragua.
   President Bush now has the opportunity of the post-Cold
War era to find a modus vivendi with Congress that doesn't
drive politics into courtrooms. He should seriously consider
a pardon for the Iran-Contra defendants, veto any more
special prosecutor laws and tell Congress that foreign policy
will again be set the old-fashioned way, by give and take
between the two political branches of government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900409-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900409-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Tucson Electric
   Auditors Note
   Firm's Problems
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2B
</SO>
<CO>
   TEP
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   TUCSON, Ariz. -- Tucson Electric Power Co.'s auditors
cited a host of contingent liabilities and uncertainties.
   In a letter to shareholders, the auditors, Deloitte &amp;
Touche, noted that the company faces various regulatory and
legal decisions as well as contractual matters.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In 1989, Tucson Electric had a loss of $89.9 million, or
$3.55 a share, on $593.7 million in revenue.
   Tucson Electric said it decided not to take charges that
last year would have resulted in a $74 million widening of
the loss. The utility said that it may decide to record a
liability for the potential charge, which involves a gain
posted years ago, a portion of which regulators now are
saying belongs to rate-payers. Tucson Electric is challenging
that ruling by the Arizona Corporation Commission.
   Also troubling the company is the $722 million investment
in the Springerville 2 coal-fired generating station. The
unit is nearing completion. However, Arizona regulators have
questioned the need for the capacity, which could result in
Tucson Electric's being barred from recovering some or all of
the unit's costs from rate-payers.
   Tucson Electric warned that "either substantial retail
rate increases or additional wholesale sales {or a
combination thereof} will be required to recover such costs"
of Springerville 2. Without recovery, "the company will
suffer increasingly deteriorating financial results, will be
unable to earn a reasonable return on its utility investment,
and will continue to have negative cash flow."
   Tucson Electric eliminated dividend payments on its common
stock earlier this year. The company has said it expects to
post losses and sees no chance of restoring the dividend in
the foreseeable future.
   Based on certain coverage tests, the company is barred
from issuing additional preferred stock. A net earnings test
also limits to about $70 million the amount of additional
first mortgage bonds that can be sold by the company, which
added that the amount of bonds it can issue under the
earnings test is expected to dwindle through this year, as
anticipated operating losses are reported.
   However, Tucson Electric said it can issue as much as $118
million of bonds by current calculation without meeting the
net earnings test, based on bonds retired after the most
recent filing of a net earnings certificate with the bond
indenture trustee.
   The company currently is trying to negotiate a new master
credit agreement that would provide as much as $350 million
of borrowing capability and would supplant all existing
short-term credit facilities.
   Current company short-term financial facilities include a
$150 million revolving bank credit agreement that expires in
May 1991, and $100 million in various bank lines expiring
from March 30 to July 31 of this year. Tucson Electric said
it is seeking a renewal of these lines until a master credit
agreement can be negotiated. Four banks holding $40 million
of debt refused to extend and were paid in December and
January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900409-0046
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900409-0046.
</DOCID>
